<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06173244 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06173244 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  WEAPON; DEVELOPMENT; COMPANY; AWARD; US; MILITARY; CONTRACT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Northrop Corp. has received a $344 million contract to continue previouslysecret development of a weapon designed to hunt down armored vehicles,officials said.;    Known as Bat, the 44-pound explosive has been underdevelopment since 1984. It would be carried aboard a missile toward its targetand then released to stalk a tank or vehicle by picking up sounds or heat fromthe target.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  NORTHROP WINS PACT TO DESIGN TANK-KILLINGWEAPON  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     By picking up sounds, it behaves much the way that a bat would, Armyofficials said Thursday.;    Northrop employs 250 workers on the program atits plant in the Los Angeles suburb of Hawthorne and plans to double itsworkforce as development continues into the mid-1990s, said Tony Cantafio, aspokesman for the company. Northrop is based in the Los Angeles area ofCentury City.;    A total of $2.2 billion would be spent on the program iffull production is funded. Officials would not say how many Bats the Army hasordered.;    Army spokesman Dave Harris said Bat is a &quot;brilliant&quot; weaponbecause it acts autonomously. Unlike &quot;smart&quot; weapons that must be guided totheir targets, the Bat is designed to find its target on its own.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Los Angeles Daily News  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Los Angeles  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910621  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  June  </MONTH><PG.COL>  15D  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  193  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday June 21, 199100173244,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>